					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I recommend either D3 or D4, on the second port, since those are available in both NES and Famicom systems (and you can then connect a standard controller on the first port without having to rewire anything). Furthermore, you can use the standard controller at the same time, without interference. I also recommend to clear bit2 of the output port so that the keyboard doesn't interfere (hardware could be designed to automatically switch between the serial bootloader and keyboard based on this signal).<br /><br />If you need to, due to &quot;Many NES controller/extension cables only connect to D0&quot;, you could provide support for D0 as well as D4 (maybe do something in the program to check which one of D0 or D4 works, before actually loading, if this is possible and/or useful).</div>

					
						<div class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="gopher://zzo38computer.org/" class="postlink">.</a></div>
